      "content_html": "<img src=\"https://cdn8.openculture.com/2026/04/21231846/Screenshot-2026-04-21-at-11.19.17-PM-1024x557.png\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n<img src=\"https://cdn8.openculture.com/2026/04/21231846/Screenshot-2026-04-21-at-11.19.17-PM-1024x557.png\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n<img src=\"https://cdn8.openculture.com/2026/04/21231846/Screenshot-2026-04-21-at-11.19.17-PM-1024x557.png\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n<img src=\"https://cdn8.openculture.com/2026/04/21231846/Screenshot-2026-04-21-at-11.19.17-PM-1024x557.png\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n<img src=\"https://cdn8.openculture.com/2026/04/21231846/Screenshot-2026-04-21-at-11.19.17-PM-1024x557.png\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\n<img src=\"https://cdn8.openculture.com/2026/04/21231846/Screenshot-2026-04-21-at-11.19.17-PM-1024x557.png\" style=\"width:100%;max-height:300px;object-fit:cover;\" />\nThough you may not hear it every day, chimera&#160;remains an evocative word, perhaps even more so for its rarity. It descends from the Greek Khimaira, literally “year-old she-goat,” the name of a mythical fire-breathing creature with a caprine body, sure enough, but also the head of a lion and the tail of a dragon. Today [&#8230;]",
